---
import Badge from "../../../components/Badge.astro";
import CaseNote from "../../../components/CaseNote.astro";
import CaseSection from "../../../components/CaseSection.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import { withBase } from "../../../lib/routes.js";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Utility Work Coordination Console | Abraham Szilagyi"
  description="A prototype case study for turning electric utility job packet data into a reviewable queue, map-backed planning surface, and handoff export."
  footerTagline="Prototype case study with public-safe demo data."
>
    <main>
      <section class="section case-hero">
        <div>
          <h1>Utility Work Coordination Console</h1>
          <p>
            A work-intake and dispatch-mapping prototype for electric utility
            overhead packets. It turns packet-derived job data into a reviewable
            registry, map, route plan, and handoff surface.
          </p>
          <div class="badge-row">
            <Badge>Prototype</Badge>
            <Badge>Public-safe demo data</Badge>
            <Badge>Not a production optimizer</Badge>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="dashboard-proof" aria-label="Utility work coordination console mockup">
          <div class="console-topbar">
            <strong>Work coordination console</strong>
            <div class="console-tabs" aria-label="Mock dashboard filters">
              <span class="console-tab active">Ready</span>
              <span class="console-tab">Needs review</span>
              <span class="console-tab">Blocked</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="console-grid">
            <aside class="console-panel">
              <span class="mock-label">Queue</span>
              <div class="queue-controls">
                <div class="fake-input">Search PM order, city, source file</div>
                <div class="fake-input">Filter: Work center · Crew type · Readiness</div>
              </div>
              <div class="console-list">
                <article class="job-row active">
                  <strong>PM-1842 · Pole replacement</strong>
                  <span>Ready · valid coordinates · overhead</span>
                </article>
                <article class="job-row">
                  <strong>PM-1916 · Crossarm repair</strong>
                  <span>Needs review · comments changed scope</span>
                </article>
                <article class="job-row">
                  <strong>PM-2031 · Guy wire issue</strong>
                  <span>Blocked · access constraint</span>
                </article>
                <article class="job-row">
                  <strong>PM-2110 · Inspection follow-up</strong>
                  <span>Ready · same work center</span>
                </article>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <section>
              <div class="console-map">
                <span class="route-line"></span>
                <span class="route-line alt"></span>
                <span class="pin one">A</span>
                <span class="pin two warn">B</span>
                <span class="pin three review">C</span>
                <span class="pin four">D</span>
              </div>
              <div class="console-detail">
                <span class="mock-label">Selected job</span>
                <div class="detail-row"><strong>Readiness</strong><span>Ready to review for dispatch</span></div>
                <div class="detail-row"><strong>Source</strong><span>Packet page 1, extracted fields</span></div>
                <div class="detail-row"><strong>Warning</strong><span>Verify latest comments before assignment</span></div>
              </div>
            </section>
            <aside class="console-panel">
              <span class="mock-label">Route handoff</span>
              <div class="route-card">
                <strong>Draft route group</strong>
                <ol>
                  <li>PM-1842 · Ready</li>
                  <li>PM-2110 · Ready</li>
                  <li>PM-1916 · Review before add</li>
                </ol>
              </div>
              <div class="route-card">
                <strong>Export includes</strong>
                <p>Stops, job facts, source references, warnings, and notes for the next review step.</p>
              </div>
            </aside>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section case-shell">
        <CaseSection
          title="Packet facts are hard to compare when each job stays buried."
        >
            <p class="case-lede">
              Electric utility job packets hold facts needed for planning, but
              they do not automatically become a dispatchable work set.
            </p>
            <p>
              A dispatcher or planner may need to know what is due, what is
              nearby, what needs review, what has valid coordinates, what is
              blocked, and what belongs together before sending work to a crew.
            </p>
            <div class="before-after">
              <CaseNote title="Separate packet documents">
                Useful fields are scattered across documents, comments, source files, and field knowledge.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Reviewable work registry">
                Jobs can be searched, filtered, mapped, reviewed, grouped, and handed off with warnings intact.
              </CaseNote>
            </div>
        </CaseSection>

        <CaseSection title="Job packet to planning surface.">
            <ul>
              <li>Packet-derived job data enters a searchable queue.</li>
              <li>Records keep source file context and review status visible.</li>
              <li>The map shows where work is, but the surrounding data explains whether it is ready.</li>
              <li>A route handoff groups jobs without claiming to solve every crew, material, permit, or outage constraint.</li>
            </ul>
        </CaseSection>

        <CaseSection title="What the prototype does now.">
          <div class="case-grid">
            <CaseNote title="Search, filter, sort">
              Operators can move beyond flipping through packet files and compare jobs in a common list.
            </CaseNote>
            <CaseNote title="Planning surface">
              Markers help compare location, readiness, warning signals, and route context together.
            </CaseNote>
            <CaseNote title="Review before trust">
              A selected job can expose extracted facts, source references, warnings, and review needs.
            </CaseNote>
            <CaseNote title="Draft route export">
              The output is a working handoff, not a claim that dispatch has been fully automated.
            </CaseNote>
          </div>
        </CaseSection>

        <CaseSection title="What this deliberately does not overclaim.">
            <ul>
              <li>It is a prototype and public-safe demo, not a production utility work-management system.</li>
              <li>It treats packet extraction as work intake, not complete dispatch context.</li>
              <li>It does not call itself a route optimizer because real routing depends on crew skill, materials, permits, access, outage needs, geography, and daily interruptions.</li>
              <li>It surfaces uncertainty instead of pretending every extracted record is ready to send to the field.</li>
            </ul>
        </CaseSection>

        <CaseSection title="A stronger readiness model.">
            <p>
              The next useful layer is not bigger visual polish. It is a better
              data contract around readiness, review, blocked reasons, work
              category, asset type, required crew type, work center, assignment,
              and status updates.
            </p>
            <p>
              That would let the console answer the more operational question:
              what can be worked now, what needs review, what is blocked, and
              what kind of crew would handle it?
            </p>
        </CaseSection>

        <CaseSection
          title="A familiar workflow can become a tool without pretending it is simple."
        >
            <p>
              This case shows the operating pattern I want the portfolio to
              prove: stay close to real work, preserve the familiar structure,
              build a small useful surface, keep the source trail visible, and
              make the handoff clearer for the next person.
            </p>
            <div class="button-row">
              <a class="button primary" href={withBase("/work/")}>Back to Work Samples</a>
              <a class="button secondary" href={withBase("/#workflow-conversation")}>About Me</a>
            </div>
        </CaseSection>
      </section>
    </main>
</SiteLayout>
